{"id":"2206.01179","submitter":"Jason South","authors":"Jason R. South","title":"Construction of the Goldbach Polynomial as an Algebraic Approach to the\n  Goldbach Conjecture","comments":"6 pages","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.GM","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  This paper will give both the necessary and sufficient conditions required to\nfind a counter-example to the Goldbach Conjecture by using an algebraic\napproach where no knowledge of the gaps between prime numbers is needed. To\nbegin, let $a \\in \\mathbb{N}$ and $a > 3$. Next assign the variable $x$ where\nfor any prime $p_i \\leq a$ there must exist some unique $q_i, \\alpha_i \\in\n\\mathbb{N}$ satisfying $x = q_i +p_i$ and $\\prod_{i = 1}^{\\pi(a)}q_i = \\prod_{i\n= 1}^{\\pi(a)}p_i^{\\alpha_i}$. The final step will be to substitute each $q_i =\nx - p_i$ into the product relationship to produce the Goldbach Polynomial\n$\\prod_{i = 1}^{\\pi(a)}(x - p_i) = \\prod_{i = 1}^{\\pi(a)}p_i^{\\alpha_i}$. It\nwill then be shown that the Goldbach Conjecture is false if and only if $2a$ is\na solution to the Goldbach Polynomial when $a \\in \\mathbb{N}$ and $a > 3$.\n  A similar method will be employed to give the necessary and sufficient\nconditions when every even number is not the difference of two primes with one\nprime being less than that even number. To begin, let $a \\in \\mathbb{N}$ and $a\n> 3$. Again, assign the variable $x$ where for any prime $p_i \\leq a$ there\nmust exist some unique $q_i, \\alpha_i \\in \\mathbb{N}$ where $x = q_i - p_i$ and\n$\\prod_{i = 1}^{\\pi(a)}q_i = (a + 1)^{\\beta(a +1)} \\prod_{i =\n1}^{\\pi(a)}p_i^{\\alpha_i}$ with the condition that the function $\\beta(a + 1)$\nis equal to one if $a + 1$ is prime and zero otherwise. The final step will be\nto substitute each $q_i = x + p_i$ into the product relationship to produce the\nGoldbach Difference Polynomial $\\prod_{i = 1}^{\\pi(a)}(x + p_i) = (a +\n1)^{\\beta(a +1)} \\prod_{i = 1}^{\\pi(a)}p_i^{\\alpha_i}$. It will then be shown\nthat every even number of the form $2a$ is not the difference of two primes\nwhere one prime is less than $a$ if and only if $2a$ is a root of the Goldbach\nDifference Polynomial when $a > 3$.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 31 May 2022 03:19:00 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 7 Jul 2022 20:21:26 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Mon, 19 Dec 2022 16:15:09 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-12-20"}
{"id":"2206.01182","submitter":"Cheng Meng","authors":"Jingyi Zhang, Cheng Meng, Jun Yu, Mengrui Zhang, Wenxuan Zhong and\n  Ping Ma","title":"An optimal transport approach for selecting a representative subsample\n  with application in efficient kernel density estimation","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"stat.ML math.ST stat.TH","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Subsampling methods aim to select a subsample as a surrogate for the observed\nsample. Such methods have been used pervasively in large-scale data analytics,\nactive learning, and privacy-preserving analysis in recent decades. Instead of\nmodel-based methods, in this paper, we study model-free subsampling methods,\nwhich aim to identify a subsample that is not confined by model assumptions.\nExisting model-free subsampling methods are usually built upon clustering\ntechniques or kernel tricks. Most of these methods suffer from either a large\ncomputational burden or a theoretical weakness. In particular, the theoretical\nweakness is that the empirical distribution of the selected subsample may not\nnecessarily converge to the population distribution. Such computational and\ntheoretical limitations hinder the broad applicability of model-free\nsubsampling methods in practice. We propose a novel model-free subsampling\nmethod by utilizing optimal transport techniques. Moreover, we develop an\nefficient subsampling algorithm that is adaptive to the unknown probability\ndensity function. Theoretically, we show the selected subsample can be used for\nefficient density estimation by deriving the convergence rate for the proposed\nsubsample kernel density estimator. We also provide the optimal bandwidth for\nthe proposed estimator. Numerical studies on synthetic and real-world datasets\ndemonstrate the performance of the proposed method is superior.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 31 May 2022 05:19:29 GMT"}],"upd